  "market_context": "GBPUSD on 1-hour chart showing a downtrend with lower highs and lower lows; analyst compares two MACD versions to highlight timing differences in divergence detection.",
  "key_observation": "Custom MACD (3,10,SMA) detected a bullish divergence (price lower lows, MACD higher lows) and a hidden bearish divergence (price lower highs, MACD higher highs) earlier than the standard MACD (12,26,EMA).",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: The analyst opened the standard MACD indicator on TradingView and reviewed its default settings (Fast=12, Slow=26, EMA-based).",
    "Step 2: The analyst modified the MACD settings to Fast=3, Slow=10, Oscillator MA Type = SMA, Signal Line MA Type = SMA, and Signal Smoothing = 16 (Linda Rashi’s settings).",
    "Step 3: The analyst added a second MACD with standard settings to the same chart for side-by-side comparison.",
    "Step 4: The analyst pointed to a specific price swing where the custom MACD printed a low while the standard MACD did not, demonstrating faster reaction.",
    "Step 5: The analyst identified a bullish divergence (price making lower lows, custom MACD making higher lows) visible earlier on the custom MACD than on the standard one.",
    "Step 6: The analyst identified a hidden bearish divergence (price making lower highs, custom MACD making higher highs) that was not visible at all on the standard MACD."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "Custom faster MACD settings (3,10,SMA) can reveal divergences earlier than standard settings, but require confirmation from price action and market structure to avoid false signals.",
